This sequence is about my experience with Patsy and how she was the Actual Girl; or, as I used to say, "The Girl the End of the World."
It was strongly infleunced by that Skeeter Davis song "The End of the World" and Dietrich Bonhoeffer's "Creation and Fall" and my own theory 
of original sin vis-vis Eliade and nuclear weapons corpus.

The LimiT
I

When I think back on Brooklyn, do you see, I do
Not think, “She’s here too, somewhere in these streets,
These trains, these bars, this ordinary weather”
Though had one told me—had one human being
Done me that simple service—I had gone
Directly to you, straight as judgment goes
To its own object; so the puzzle is not that
You were not there, but what had happened to me
Where you were concerned, what twist, what damage, what
Deflection in the faculty itself, that I,
Who could have crossed a borough for one fact,
Lived in a place containing you and yet
Containing you not for me. That is the riddle,
And Brooklyn, for that reason, is no place now but a proof withheld.

II

For proof withheld makes worlds; and thus, if one
Would hide one person perfectly, why, one need not
Blow out the lamps, nor call the blackout wardens, nor
Do anything theatrical at all—just let
The streets proceed as streets, the river do
Its river-work, the trains arrive and leave,
The borough keep its countenance, and by that very
Continuance of the usual make the cut
More absolute than darkness could; and so
There came to be, from one omission, two
Earths, yes, two planets called the same thing, Earth,
Hurtling at one another, not in space
So much as in significance, until
The whole borough, by collision, is annihilated in the mind.

III

Now at the table first the matter showed
Its ethical edge. I ask the name; you give
The first one. I ask for the last. Then came
That hesitation—not, I think, from vanity,
Nor childish shame, but from experience, the old
Knowledge of what a room does when a name
Arrives too charged, too culturally prepared,
Too full of other people’s stupid little
Store of echoes, questions, pleasures, all
The ways a listener may fail before
The person finishes appearing. Yet
You did not harden, did not make a scene,
Did not withdraw your presence from the test.
You took one breath and, without losing your precision, went on.

IV

And there, if anywhere, your generosity
Showed—not as sweetness, no, nor indulgence, nor
Any of those lax virtues men praise most
When they have done least to deserve them, but
As pain borne in form. It was painful to you
To think I might make that mistake; I see
That now; and still you let the moment stand
Open enough that I might not. I did
Not drop the quarter in the jukebox. No.
I thought, Don’t say that. She is too fine. That was
My answer, if an answer. Was it enough?
Who knows? But understand me: not to vulgarize
The other person may already be
A kind of fidelity, even where the whole event remains unresolved.

V

So Bonhoeffer comes in—not dragged by force
But because he belongs. Before they hanged him on
The steel, he wrote about the limit of
The other person, Paradise somewhere there,
At the edge where one must stop if one would
Keep the other other; and with you
That was no metaphor, no scholarly
Decoration dropped over private feeling.
A limit was established. Perfectly.
You crossed it coming toward me; crossed back over
It going away; and by going away
Marked it forever. Whether I failed it? Wait.
I did not necessarily fail. The limit may
Be met, in part, and tragedy still intervene to seal the rest.

VI

Because there was tragedy, there was bad
Information. You, I think, had good intelligence
On me; I, on you, had rotten stuff, fed in
By some third hand—someone who knew more than
I did and shaped the whole catastrophe
Before I ever reached the table. So
If on the second time you came at me
At seven hundred fifty miles an hour—say
That plainly, since nothing less gives the fact—
And if your body said, Just follow me,
Or not at all, while mine stood there, arrested,
The judgment cannot be as simple as
He failed, she vanished. No. He may have passed
One test and then been barred from what came next by history.

VII

Still, I am left with this: I knew you, then
I didn’t; then, much later, I remembered
You—not as one remembers a whole life,
By sequence, file, organization, but
Through one crowning tableau without which I could
Not form the thought of you at all; and from
That scene the rest came back in broken order,
Like a stream that runs downhill, then up
Mystery Hill, then down again, as if
The river had a mind beyond gravity.
So every time I go back into it
I do not find explanation. I find
Your beauty and think, That’s it. That is the limit.
No more confusion can improve on what was drawn there.

VIII

And beauty, mind you, not as ornament
But as force. The whole difficulty with
Your name belonged there too. Patsy Cline should
Be fine, but somehow it isn’t; the name
Should do the work, suffice, arrive and fit,
Yet one can feel how listeners hear it first,
And hearing first, hear wrongly; so the pause
Before the surname almost showed what Babel is—
Not confusion merely, but language working
Too quickly on the wrong object, the name
Descending while the person still arrives.
I, Terrence Ross, get off easy enough.
No myth runs in before me. But with you
The given word was true and still too small for the fact.

IX

Then comes the greater scale. For when I say
I cannot be alone like this on Earth
With just this one woman for whom my love
Transits the stars, I do not mean romance
Inflated by philosophy. I mean
The order of experience itself
Compelling rank. There would be this one person,
This one, who mattered more than anyone else,
Who drove me to the limit; and from that
The thought followed—not coldly, not against
The world, but by exact precedence—
I would save you alone from the Thing itself,
And all the rest could come along. That is
Not cruelty. That is scale. That is the truth the age hates most.

X

Which brings me to the do-over. For the only
Way I could stay true to you, follow you,
Without collapsing into one-life rhetoric
And all the prophets of the once-for-all,
Was to believe there would be one more time.
Why not? The song ends; people cry for more.
The game hands out ten thousand extra lives.
And who are these that run around declaring
We only live once, as if they had been dead
And come back with the paperwork complete?
I had a memory. I came around
The side of the old house like a clear bubble, saw
The dark-green swing-set Dad had welded, Mom
In her long dress, and Dad gently swinging her.

XI

And in her womb there was a galactic swirl
Of light—and I went right for it. So no,
I do not take the doctrine of one shot
As settled law. I have seen entrance. I
Have seen, or think I have, what it is to come
In. Therefore when I say eternal return,
Or that I must get back to the table with you,
I am not playing games with longing. I
Am saying there are precedents in me
For re-entry, for correction, for a life
In which the information is set right,
The third person does not compose the tragedy,
The borough is not blacked out to hide one face,
And I arrive on time enough to know what stands before me.

XII

So let the whole thing stand as it occurred—
Or rather, as it still occurs, since this
One strange river is the only one left running
In the world I know. The table, the breath,
The name with blanks, the borough split in two,
The blackout made for one, the speed, the line,
The do-over, the swing, the blue sky, the cards,
The bomb behind it all, the end of the world
Reduced—if reduced is the word—to one man,
One woman, one limit perfectly established:
Treat that as real, because it was. And then
See what follows. Not confession merely, nor
Failure merely, but testimony from
An ethics at the end of the world, where you remained the proof.
